\par
As I said, it was months after that Rupert Grant suddenly entered\par
my room, swinging a satchel in his hand and with a general air\par
of having jumped over the garden wall, and implored me to go with\par
him upon the latest and wildest of his expeditions.  He proposed\par
to himself no less a thing than the discovery of the actual origin,\par
whereabouts, and headquarters of the source of all our joys and sorrows--\par
the Club of Queer Trades.  I should expand this story for ever if I\par
explained how ultimately we ran this strange entity to its lair.\par
The process meant a hundred interesting things.  The tracking\par
of a member, the bribing of a cabman, the fighting of roughs,\par
the lifting of a paving stone, the finding of a cellar, the finding\par
of a cellar below the cellar, the finding of the subterranean passage,\par
the finding of the Club of Queer Trades.\par
\par
I have had many strange experiences in my life, but never a stranger\par
one than that I felt when I came out of those rambling, sightless,\par
and seemingly hopeless passages into the sudden splendour of a sumptuous\par
and hospitable dining-room, surrounded upon almost every side by faces\par
that I knew.  There was Mr Montmorency, the Arboreal House-Agent,\par
seated between the two brisk young men who were occasionally vicars,\par
and always Professional Detainers.  There was Mr P. G. Northover,\par
founder of the Adventure and Romance Agency.  There was Professor Chadd,\par
who invented the dancing Language.\par
\par
As we entered, all the members seemed to sink suddenly into their chairs,\par
and with the very action the vacancy of the presidential seat gaped\par
at us like a missing tooth.\par
\par
"The president's not here," said Mr P. G. Northover, turning suddenly\par
to Professor Chadd.\par
\par
"N--no," said the philosopher, with more than his ordinary vagueness.\par
"I can't imagine where he is."\par
\par
"Good heavens," said Mr Montmorency, jumping up, "I really feel\par
a little nervous.  I'll go and see."  And he ran out of the room.\par
\par
An instant after he ran back again, twittering with a timid ecstasy.\par
\par
"He's there, gentlemen--he's there all right--he's coming in now,"\par
he cried, and sat down.  Rupert and I could hardly help feeling\par
the beginnings of a sort of wonder as to who this person\par
might be who was the first member of this insane brotherhood.\par
Who, we thought indistinctly, could be maddest in this world of madmen:\par
what fantastic was it whose shadow filled all these fantastics\par
with so loyal an expectation?\par
\par
Suddenly we were answered.  The door flew open and the room was\par
filled and shaken with a shout, in the midst of which Basil Grant,\par
smiling and in evening dress, took his seat at the head of the table.\par
\par
How we ate that dinner I have no idea.  In the common way I am a person\par
particularly prone to enjoy the long luxuriance of the club dinner.\par
But on this occasion it seemed a hopeless and endless string\par
of courses.  Hors-d'oeuvre sardines seemed as big as herrings,\par
soup seemed a sort of ocean, larks were ducks, ducks were ostriches\par
until that dinner was over.  The cheese course was maddening.\par
I had often heard of the moon being made of green cheese.\par
That night I thought the green cheese was made of the moon.\par
And all the time Basil Grant went on laughing and eating and drinking,\par
and never threw one glance at us to tell us why he was there,\par
the king of these capering idiots.\par
\par
At last came the moment which I knew must in some way enlighten us,\par
the time of the club speeches and the club toasts.  Basil Grant\par
rose to his feet amid a surge of songs and cheers.\par
\par
"Gentlemen," he said, "it is a custom in this society that the president\par
for the year opens the proceedings not by any general toast of sentiment,\par
but by calling upon each member to give a brief account of his trade.\par
We then drink to that calling and to all who follow it.\par
It is my business, as the senior member, to open by stating my claim\par
to membership of this club.  Years ago, gentlemen, I was a judge;\par
I did my best in that capacity to do justice and to administer the law.\par
But it gradually dawned on me that in my work, as it was, I was\par
not touching even the fringe of justice.  I was seated in the seat\par
of the mighty, I was robed in scarlet and ermine; nevertheless, I held\par
a small and lowly and futile post.  I had to go by a mean rule as much\par
as a postman, and my red and gold was worth no more than his.\par
Daily there passed before me taut and passionate problems,\par
the stringency of which I had to pretend to relieve by silly\par
imprisonments or silly damages, while I knew all the time, by the light\par
of my living common sense, that they would have been far better\par
relieved by a kiss or a thrashing, or a few words of explanation,\par
or a duel, or a tour in the West Highlands.  Then, as this grew on me,\par
there grew on me continuously the sense of a mountainous frivolity.\par
Every word said in the court, a whisper or an oath,\par
seemed more connected with life than the words I had to say.\par
Then came the time when I publicly blasphemed the whole bosh,\par
was classed as a madman and melted from public life."\par
\par
Something in the atmosphere told me that it was not only Rupert\par
and I who were listening with intensity to this statement.\par
\par
"Well, I discovered that I could be of no real use.  I offered myself\par
privately as a purely moral judge to settle purely moral differences.\par
Before very long these unofficial courts of honour (kept strictly secret)\par
had spread over the whole of society.  People were tried before me not\par
for the practical trifles for which nobody cares, such as committing\par
a murder, or keeping a dog without a licence.  My criminals were\par
tried for the faults which really make social life impossible.\par
They were tried before me for selfishness, or for an impossible vanity,\par
or for scandalmongering, or for stinginess to guests or dependents.\par
Of course these courts had no sort of real coercive powers.\par
The fulfilment of their punishments rested entirely on the honour of\par
the ladies and gentlemen involved, including the honour of the culprits.\par
But you would be amazed to know how completely our orders were\par
always obeyed.  Only lately I had a most pleasing example.\par
A maiden lady in South Kensington whom I had condemned to solitary\par
confinement for being the means of breaking off an engagement\par
through backbiting, absolutely refused to leave her prison,\par
although some well-meaning persons had been inopportune enough\par
to rescue her."\par
\par
Rupert Grant was staring at his brother, his mouth fallen agape.\par
So, for the matter of that, I expect, was I. This, then, was the\par
explanation of the old lady's strange discontent and her still\par
stranger content with her lot.  She was one of the culprits\par
of his Voluntary Criminal Court.  She was one of the clients\par
of his Queer Trade.\par
\par
We were still dazed when we drank, amid a crash of glasses,\par
the health of Basil's new judiciary.  We had only a confused sense\par
of everything having been put right, the sense men will have when they\par
come into the presence of God.  We dimly heard Basil say:\par
\par
"Mr P. G. Northover will now explain the Adventure and Romance Agency."\par
\par
And we heard equally dimly Northover beginning the statement he had\par
made long ago to Major Brown.  Thus our epic ended where it had begun,\par
like a true cycle.\par
